I would mention something that might be of interest to you but your Twitter account doesn't allow DMs

IST is a very interesting company with expertise you might be interested in. It was run by my long term friend Derek Lambert and co writer of compilers until his death. His boast was that he knew Bill Gates when he was just a millionaire. They are in UK and Palo Alto.

OK. I still write software, but for amusement. The company developed commercial software for credit management for banks and direct marketing including demographic analysis and targeting. A bit like Cambridge Analytica.

This is amazing! You mentioned you owned a company, what was it called? What was the main area of expertise? Just to be clear, we were doubting that you were too old, not that you developed compilers!
Jack Harwell had a language named after him; Language H. I am mentioned in this link http://www. geonius.com/emett/guide.ht ml …
I also worked with IST, a spin off from Imperial College. http://www. ist.co.uk/customer/index .html …
All that is apart from running large projects, designing systems, programming on commercial systems. Having been in business since 1971, I ended up owning and running a software company.
I worked in ICI treasury department to design a computer language for accounts to be able to run financial consolidation. Then produced a compiler written in EPS/FCS on a Data General.
I designed a system to find all opportunities to travel across the BR train network and used actual ticket sales to cost each piece of rail.

Then worked on an automatic flowcharting system for JHDP, based on directed graph algorithms. Later I ran the project and wrote the code generator for a NEAT to PLAN cross compiler with some friends as a subcontract from ICL Dataskil.

Really. I started in IT in 1965 as a programmer. Then went to work for JHDP, Jack Harwell (single digit BCS membership number). Worked on the first privately written COBOL compiler. Wrote the translator pass. Whole thing took a year with 10 people.
We doubt that completely! :)

Used to design and develop compilers and cross compilers, including designing a language for financial consolidation and writing the compiler. Interesting job, but I am too old for that sort of thing.
